data: {"type":"synthesis","modelId":"local/apple-fm","model":"Crucible","text":"## Zod Schema for IPv4 Address Validation\n\n```json\n{\n  \"$schema\": \"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\",\n  \"title\": \"IPv4 Address\",\n  \"type\": \"object\",\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"address\": {\n      \"type\": \"string\",\n      \"pattern\": \"^(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9]{2}){3}$\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"required\": [\"address\"]\n}\n```\n\n## Explanation\n\n- **$schema**: Specifies the JSON Schema version used.\n- **title**: A descriptive title for the schema.\n- **type**: Indicates that the schema is an object.\n- **properties**: Defines the properties of the object.\n  - **address**: A required property of type string.\n  - **pattern**: A regular expression pattern that matches a valid IPv4 address.\n    - `^(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9]{2}){3}$`: Matches an IPv4 address with 3 sets of 1 to 4 digits, where each set can be 0-255.\n- **required**: Specifies that the `address` property is mandatory.\n\n## Usage\n\nYou can use this schema to validate IPv4 addresses in your applications. For example, in a TypeScript function, you can use the `parse()` method to validate an IPv4 address:\n\n```typescript\nconst ipv4Address = \"192.168.1.1\";\nconst isValid = ipv4Address.match(/^(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9]{2}){3}$/);\nconsole.log(isValid); // Output: true\n```\n\nThis function checks if the provided IPv4 address matches the pattern defined in the schema.","done":true,"replace":true}

